1
00:00:48,760 --> 00:00:50,440
Come on, you lazy Kaffirs.
Come on.

2
00:00:51,760 --> 00:00:53,360
Keep in line, man. Keep in line.

3
00:00:53,440 --> 00:00:55,800
What are you looking at me
like that for, you fuck?

4
00:00:55,920 --> 00:00:58,360
What are you looking at?
I'll fuck you up!

5
00:00:58,480 --> 00:00:59,920
Move!

6
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:04,200
You men make sure
that's tied down properly, you hear me?

7
00:01:07,840 --> 00:01:09,040
Careful, man!

8
00:01:09,160 --> 00:01:12,440
- Pa, why is it taking so long?
- Go back to your mother.

9
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:14,800
Move your feet, move your feet, come on!

10
00:01:14,920 --> 00:01:16,080
I said, go back!

11
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:17,080
Move!

12
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:23,160
Sergeant Gregory, Dannie Bosman,
the old skipper for the crossing.

13
00:01:23,280 --> 00:01:27,120
- Your first time to Robben Island?
- I hear the fishing is excellent.

14
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:29,080
- You'll get bored with that soon enough.
- Ah.

15
00:01:29,200 --> 00:01:30,600
What prison are you from?

16
00:01:30,680 --> 00:01:32,600
Kroonstad Maximum Security.

17
00:01:32,680 --> 00:01:35,880
Well, Robben Island
is a totally different ball game.

18
00:01:36,720 --> 00:01:39,360
All prisoners below deck and secured,
Captain.

19
00:01:39,480 --> 00:01:42,280
Ladies and children, all aboard please!

20
00:01:47,600 --> 00:01:50,640
- Where's your mom?
- Busy putting on her lipstick.

21
00:01:50,760 --> 00:01:52,680
We can board now, sweetie.

22
00:01:53,440 --> 00:01:56,320
- How do I look?
- You look great.

23
00:01:57,280 --> 00:01:59,000
- As long as I don't get seasick.
- It's only an hour.

24
00:01:59,120 --> 00:02:01,800
- Will I be able to get my own bedroom, Pa?
- Of course you will.

25
00:02:01,880 --> 00:02:03,440
I don't want to share with Natasha again.

26
00:02:03,520 --> 00:02:04,920
Who said I want to share with you?

27
00:02:05,040 --> 00:02:07,720
You two stop fighting
and behave yourselves.

28
00:02:07,800 --> 00:02:09,960
Remember, first impressions are everything.

29
00:02:26,120 --> 00:02:28,160
Are all the prisoners
on the island black, Ma?

30
00:02:28,280 --> 00:02:30,640
- All of them.
- But at Kroonstad, they were white.

31
00:02:30,720 --> 00:02:33,200
Now, we don't mix whites and blacks,
not even in the prisons.

32
00:02:33,280 --> 00:02:36,560
These are not just criminals, Brent.
These are terrorists.

33
00:02:37,320 --> 00:02:39,240
But what's the difference?

34
00:02:40,040 --> 00:02:41,840
Terrorists are terrible people.

35
00:02:41,920 --> 00:02:44,400
They want to kill all the whites
and take our land away from us.

36
00:02:44,480 --> 00:02:46,000
Which is why we lock them up on the island.

37
00:02:52,680 --> 00:02:54,240
Sergeant Gregory.

38
00:02:55,200 --> 00:02:57,800
Captain Devett,
the personnel officer on the island.

39
00:02:57,880 --> 00:02:59,520
How do you do, Captain? I'm Gloria...

40
00:02:59,640 --> 00:03:02,800
I have a jeep standing by. This way.
Your furniture will follow.

41
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:15,680
One, two.

42
00:03:18,520 --> 00:03:19,640
All aboard, Captain.

43
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:46,440
This is it.

44
00:03:50,360 --> 00:03:52,240
You can stand down for today, Sergeant.

45
00:03:52,360 --> 00:03:56,000
<i>This evening you're expected to attend
an officer's braai at the OC's residence.</i>

46
00:03:56,120 --> 00:03:58,400
Missus included. Full dress uniform.

47
00:04:05,200 --> 00:04:07,680
Gloria, I can't find my step-outs.

48
00:04:08,400 --> 00:04:10,080
Ma is visiting next door, Pa.

49
00:04:11,040 --> 00:04:13,480
Why the toilet outside, Pa?

50
00:04:13,560 --> 00:04:16,360
<i>These houses are old, boet.
They were built during the war.</i>

51
00:04:16,440 --> 00:04:18,720
- What war?
- Second World War.

52
00:04:18,840 --> 00:04:22,080
- But what happens if I need to go at night?
- Then you'll go.

53
00:04:22,200 --> 00:04:24,360
But there are bad people out there.

54
00:04:24,440 --> 00:04:27,320
Boy, the only bad people on this island
are locked up in jail, okay?

55
00:04:27,400 --> 00:04:29,240
Okay, Pa.

56
00:04:29,360 --> 00:04:30,640
James, are you decent?

57
00:04:30,760 --> 00:04:31,720
Yeah, why?

58
00:04:31,800 --> 00:04:33,720
Excuse all the boxes,
but you know how it is.

59
00:04:33,840 --> 00:04:34,880
This is my husband, James.

60
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:36,320
- How do you do?
- How do you do?

61
00:04:36,440 --> 00:04:39,320
- Sannie's kindly offered to baby-sit for us.
- Oh, that's very nice.

62
00:04:39,440 --> 00:04:40,760
Well, Sannie's husband is head chef here.

63
00:04:40,840 --> 00:04:44,120
So, if you ever need anything,
eggs, flour, sugar, you know who to ask.

64
00:04:44,240 --> 00:04:46,480
Just don't say where it came from.

65
00:04:46,600 --> 00:04:48,960
- I can't find my step-outs.
- Under the bed. I polished them.

66
00:04:49,080 --> 00:04:51,600
- And you, James, what's your posting?
- He doesn't know yet.

67
00:04:51,720 --> 00:04:53,360
We'll probably find out this evening.

68
00:04:53,480 --> 00:04:54,960
He must be something special,

69
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:58,000
'cause the NCOs are never invited
to the Colonel's house.

70
00:04:58,120 --> 00:05:00,480
Not unless they are in deep trouble.

71
00:05:00,600 --> 00:05:02,440
- Serious?
- We don't mix.

72
00:05:02,520 --> 00:05:04,720
Officers here are all bloody snobs.

73
00:05:04,800 --> 00:05:07,840
I've got dinner on the stove. Give me
a shout when you're ready to go, Gloria.

74
00:05:07,960 --> 00:05:09,760
All right. Thanks, Sannie.

75
00:05:11,080 --> 00:05:12,920
Well, I'm starting to get a bit nervous now.

76
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:15,800
You get in with the officers
and they'll nominate you for a commission.

77
00:05:15,880 --> 00:05:17,360
You have to be a warrant officer first, Gloria.

78
00:05:17,480 --> 00:05:19,640
This is not Worcester, James.

79
00:05:19,760 --> 00:05:21,840
This is not Kroonstad.

80
00:05:21,960 --> 00:05:24,760
This is Robben Island,
the number one prison in the country.

81
00:05:24,880 --> 00:05:26,520
You play your cards right and who knows,

82
00:05:26,640 --> 00:05:29,520
in five years you could be at head office
in Pretoria.

83
00:05:29,640 --> 00:05:30,840
Dream on.

84
00:05:30,960 --> 00:05:32,960
I think I'm going to give you
a quick little haircut before we go.

85
00:05:33,080 --> 00:05:34,040
Christ, woman, you never stop.

86
00:05:34,160 --> 00:05:36,440
- Oh, come on.
- Never.

87
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:38,320
You don't have to wait
to go to the mainland.

88
00:05:38,400 --> 00:05:40,400
I'm a fully qualified hairdresser.

89
00:05:40,520 --> 00:05:42,960
- Really?
- And I'm good.

90
00:05:44,880 --> 00:05:48,640
Highlights is what you need. A bit of flair,
then you'll see the heads turning.

91
00:05:49,720 --> 00:05:51,440
Well, are we going to keep you busy,
or what?

92
00:05:51,560 --> 00:05:53,280
This is no holiday camp, Sergeant.

93
00:05:53,400 --> 00:05:56,080
You got warders stuck out here
for two weeks at a time.

94
00:05:56,160 --> 00:05:58,080
It's a recipe for alcohol abuse,
for prostitution...

95
00:05:58,200 --> 00:05:59,120
Prostitution?

96
00:05:59,200 --> 00:06:02,640
We've got married NCOs pimping
their wives out to single warders

97
00:06:02,720 --> 00:06:05,480
to supplementing their shitty salaries.

98
00:06:05,560 --> 00:06:08,120
I hope Captain Devett
is not painting too bad a picture of us.

99
00:06:08,240 --> 00:06:10,800
- Welcome to the island, Gregory.
- It's an honor to be here, sir.

100
00:06:10,920 --> 00:06:13,240
I see our wives are already making friends.

101
00:06:14,800 --> 00:06:16,080
Thank you for inviting us, sir.

102
00:06:16,160 --> 00:06:19,160
There's someone who wants to meet you.
Excuse us, Captain.

103
00:06:19,280 --> 00:06:23,040
This is Major Piet Jordaan,
from the Bureau of State Security.

104
00:06:25,720 --> 00:06:28,000
I believe you speak
the Kaffir languages, Sergeant.

105
00:06:28,120 --> 00:06:30,600
- I speak Xhosa, sir.
- Where did you learn the language?

106
00:06:30,680 --> 00:06:33,120
I grew up on a cattle farm in Transkei.

107
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:37,520
When you've got no brothers to play with,
you end up playing with the Kaffirs, sir.

108
00:06:37,600 --> 00:06:39,920
Shall we take a walk, Sergeant?

109
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:43,360
So, what do you think of the judgment
handed down in Mandela's trial?

110
00:06:44,120 --> 00:06:46,480
In my opinion,
he should have got the rope, sir.

111
00:06:46,560 --> 00:06:48,680
Oh, then we could have turned him
into a martyr.

112
00:06:48,760 --> 00:06:51,240
Perhaps he's more use to us behind bars.

113
00:06:51,320 --> 00:06:54,200
That's a waste of taxpayers' money,
is what I say. They all are.

114
00:06:54,280 --> 00:06:55,200
All blacks?

115
00:06:55,320 --> 00:06:58,240
Certainly the ones who took up
arms against us. The communists.

116
00:06:58,360 --> 00:07:00,920
Mandela denies he's a communist.

117
00:07:01,040 --> 00:07:03,400
Well, they're all liars, aren't they?

118
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:07,440
You know, in the 1800s,
this whole island was a leper colony.

119
00:07:07,520 --> 00:07:09,640
Nothing's really changed then.

120
00:07:13,840 --> 00:07:17,240
How do you feel about heading up
the censorship office in B-section?

121
00:07:17,800 --> 00:07:20,560
Excuse my ignorance, sir,
but what is B-section?

122
00:07:21,040 --> 00:07:23,200
That's where we keep Mandela
and all his mates.

123
00:07:23,320 --> 00:07:26,240
I need someone on the inside,
someone who speaks their language.

124
00:07:26,360 --> 00:07:30,000
I want to know what they think,
how they think.

125
00:07:31,240 --> 00:07:35,080
Anything you find odd in their letters
or their visits,

126
00:07:35,160 --> 00:07:36,720
you report directly back to me.

127
00:07:37,880 --> 00:07:41,360
I want you to be my window into their soul,
if they have a soul.

128
00:07:43,160 --> 00:07:44,080
And here I was thinking

129
00:07:44,160 --> 00:07:46,600
I was going to spend my first year
working bloody nightshifts.

130
00:07:46,680 --> 00:07:49,840
- You can if you want.
- No. Please, no, sir.

131
00:07:51,080 --> 00:07:54,040
It would be an honor for me
to run the censorship office.

132
00:07:54,160 --> 00:07:55,160
I won't let you down.

133
00:07:55,280 --> 00:07:57,960
You let me down,
you let your country down.

134
00:07:58,720 --> 00:08:02,520
- I would never do such a thing.
- Of course not.

135
00:08:03,520 --> 00:08:06,480
Well, I don't know about you,
but I'm bloody starving.

136
00:08:06,560 --> 00:08:07,920
Let's go and get something to eat.

137
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:13,560
- They asleep?
- Finally.

138
00:08:13,680 --> 00:08:15,280
Too much bloody excitement.

139
00:08:15,400 --> 00:08:18,040
The Colonel's wife, Joyce,
is coming over tomorrow for a cut.

140
00:08:18,160 --> 00:08:19,760
She bakes so she'll pay with a cake.

141
00:08:19,880 --> 00:08:22,000
And Hettie,
you know that nice captain's wife?

142
00:08:22,080 --> 00:08:23,480
Her husband dives for crayfish

143
00:08:23,560 --> 00:08:26,240
so that's how she'll pay.
And that woman with the gray hair...

144
00:08:26,360 --> 00:08:28,240
- Gloria.
- What?

145
00:08:28,360 --> 00:08:31,240
They're putting me with Mandela and Sisulu
and them.

146
00:08:31,320 --> 00:08:33,000
No.

147
00:08:33,080 --> 00:08:35,120
They want me in charge
of the censorship office.

148
00:08:35,240 --> 00:08:37,280
My God, James,
why didn't you say something?

149
00:08:38,480 --> 00:08:41,360
Wasn't going to blow my trumpet
in front of all those bloody officers.

150
00:08:41,440 --> 00:08:43,720
This is big, my boy. Mandela.

151
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:46,000
Never mind that, I report directly to Pretoria.

152
00:08:47,640 --> 00:08:50,600
This is fantastic.
Did they say anything about a promotion?

153
00:08:50,680 --> 00:08:52,120
In due course, I was told.

154
00:08:54,480 --> 00:08:56,160
No more discipline order for me.

155
00:08:57,160 --> 00:09:00,240
From now on, I'm in charge of the worst
terrorist this country's ever seen.

156
00:09:01,560 --> 00:09:02,880
Do you know how many bridges
he's blown up?

157
00:09:03,680 --> 00:09:05,200
Do you know how many police stations

158
00:09:05,320 --> 00:09:07,320
<i>he and his Umkhonto we Sizwe
have bombed?</i>

159
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:14,360
Didn't I say this was going to be our island
in the sun? Didn't I say that, James?

160
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:16,280
You sure did, Booky.

161
00:09:30,240 --> 00:09:33,080
Put your backs into it, you lazy Kaffirs!

162
00:09:40,840 --> 00:09:42,960
Get up, you slack bastards!

163
00:09:45,720 --> 00:09:48,080
Three days off rations for insubordination.

164
00:09:49,240 --> 00:09:50,680
Attention!

165
00:09:56,600 --> 00:09:58,520
I'm your new censorship officer!

166
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:02,600
If you want to post a letter,
you do it through me!

167
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:07,920
One letter every six months,
no longer than 500 words.

168
00:10:09,320 --> 00:10:13,760
No reference to other prisoners,
no mention of prison conditions.

169
00:10:16,480 --> 00:10:18,200
And no bloody politics.

170
00:10:20,920 --> 00:10:25,640
If you fail to adhere to these regulations,
your letters will not be posted.

171
00:10:29,720 --> 00:10:32,680
If you receive a letter, it comes through me.

172
00:10:33,560 --> 00:10:35,600
Same story. One every six months.

173
00:10:37,560 --> 00:10:40,920
Any mention of politics
and that letter will be censored.

174
00:10:41,880 --> 00:10:42,800
Is that clear?

175
00:10:44,600 --> 00:10:48,720
You fuck with me and I'll make your life
a lot more miserable than it already is.

176
00:10:50,040 --> 00:10:51,720
And I'll enjoy doing so.

177
00:10:55,200 --> 00:10:56,400
Which one is Mandela?

178
00:10:56,480 --> 00:10:59,880
He's in solitary.
Five days for talking in the passage.

179
00:11:02,400 --> 00:11:05,000
Right! Back to work!

180
00:11:05,800 --> 00:11:08,360
Let's see you breaking some rocks!

181
00:11:15,480 --> 00:11:18,000
Last one on the right.
It's nice and damp in there.

182
00:11:24,760 --> 00:11:25,960
Hey, you.

183
00:11:33,200 --> 00:11:34,960
I'm talking to you, man. Look at me!

184
00:11:44,120 --> 00:11:45,760
I'll see you, Mandela

185
00:12:13,120 --> 00:12:16,080
Mrs. Mandela, Sergeant Gregory.
I'll be monitoring your visit.

186
00:12:16,240 --> 00:12:18,080
- How do you do, Sergeant?
- Follow me.

187
00:12:24,400 --> 00:12:29,400
Vosloo, let's call prisoner 466l64 to Booth 3.
Here, please.

188
00:12:34,800 --> 00:12:36,120
You speak only in English.

189
00:12:37,840 --> 00:12:39,560
And only about family matters.

190
00:12:47,960 --> 00:12:49,200
Prisoner ready.

191
00:12:54,160 --> 00:12:56,480
You have 30 minutes, starting now.

192
00:13:06,600 --> 00:13:09,720
<i>- How are you, Madiba?
- Compose yourself.</i>

193
00:13:09,840 --> 00:13:12,680
<i>We don't have much time.</i>

194
00:13:12,760 --> 00:13:14,800
<i>How are our daughters?</i>

195
00:13:16,120 --> 00:13:17,320
They can't sleep at night.

196
00:13:17,400 --> 00:13:20,040
Terrified the security will come
and bash down our door.

197
00:13:20,120 --> 00:13:21,840
That is political, Mrs. Mandela.

198
00:13:21,960 --> 00:13:23,800
<i>It is not. It is about our family.</i>

199
00:13:28,080 --> 00:13:30,920
There is too much harassment
from all sides all the time.

200
00:13:32,200 --> 00:13:33,360
It is upsetting the girls.

201
00:13:34,440 --> 00:13:37,240
George Bizos suggests we send them
to a boarding school in Swaziland.

202
00:13:38,000 --> 00:13:39,600
<i>They'll come home on holidays.</i>

203
00:13:40,400 --> 00:13:41,960
<i>Will you cope being alone?</i>

204
00:13:44,440 --> 00:13:48,440
When I married you,
I knew I was marrying the struggle.

205
00:13:51,480 --> 00:13:52,920
<i>Have you heard from Evelyn?</i>

206
00:13:53,040 --> 00:13:55,880
She has a job at the mines, typing.

207
00:13:55,960 --> 00:13:57,840
Thembi came to visit.

208
00:13:59,480 --> 00:14:00,920
<i>How is my son?</i>

209
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:02,320
He's a man now.

210
00:14:02,400 --> 00:14:04,880
<i>He has his driver's license and his own car.</i>

211
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:08,320
<i>Tell him I'm allowed another visit
in six months' time.</i>

212
00:14:08,440 --> 00:14:10,520
<i>He has to put in an application.</i>

213
00:14:10,640 --> 00:14:12,120
I will tell him.

214
00:14:13,720 --> 00:14:15,760
<i>How are our friends in Lusaka?</i>

215
00:14:16,560 --> 00:14:19,120
Oliver has been appointed
President General of the ANC.

216
00:14:19,800 --> 00:14:21,160
<i>English only.</i>

217
00:14:22,360 --> 00:14:27,280
<i>Tell Oliver that all of us in here
agree he should escalate the armed struggle.</i>

218
00:14:27,560 --> 00:14:30,280
<i>The people must make
this country ungovernable.</i>

219
00:14:30,360 --> 00:14:31,600
That's it.

220
00:14:32,360 --> 00:14:34,000
Vosloo, this visit is terminated.

221
00:14:36,920 --> 00:14:38,040
This way, please.

222
00:14:38,160 --> 00:14:40,720
No, please,
we were talking about family matters.

223
00:14:40,840 --> 00:14:42,680
Do you think I'm stupid?

224
00:14:43,160 --> 00:14:45,440
Vosloo, escort the prisoner back to his cell.
Follow me.

225
00:14:45,560 --> 00:14:47,400
On your feet, Mandela, move!

226
00:15:05,680 --> 00:15:06,800
Gregory!

227
00:15:15,040 --> 00:15:18,360
- That was quick.
- They started talking in Xhosa.

228
00:15:18,480 --> 00:15:19,600
About what?

229
00:15:19,680 --> 00:15:23,960
Mandela told her to instruct Oliver Tambo
to escalate the armed struggle.

230
00:15:24,040 --> 00:15:27,040
He said they must make
the country ungovernable.

231
00:15:27,160 --> 00:15:29,760
- Anything else?
- Family stuff.

232
00:15:29,880 --> 00:15:32,440
Kids going off to boarding school,
that sort of thing.

233
00:15:32,560 --> 00:15:36,760
When Winnie gets back to Joburg,
she's going to be detained indefinitely.

234
00:15:36,880 --> 00:15:40,400
It's going to be front-page news.
I'll send you a clipping.

235
00:15:40,960 --> 00:15:42,280
Make sure Mandela gets it.

236
00:15:44,240 --> 00:15:45,520
No problem.

237
00:15:46,600 --> 00:15:48,720
Oh, one small thing.

238
00:15:49,240 --> 00:15:51,960
She mentioned his son Thembi,
the one from his first marriage.

239
00:15:52,080 --> 00:15:54,480
He's got his driver's license.
He even has his own car.

240
00:15:55,720 --> 00:15:58,960
- He probably stole the bloody thing.
- Right.

241
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:08,080
Highlights really
look fantastic on you.

242
00:16:08,160 --> 00:16:11,000
- Hello, sweetie.
- Ladies.

243
00:16:11,480 --> 00:16:13,760
- How was your day?
- Good. Where are the kids?

244
00:16:13,880 --> 00:16:16,560
Switch on the kettle, won't you?
Make us all a nice cup of tea.

245
00:16:16,680 --> 00:16:19,600
- What do you think, James?
- About what?

246
00:16:19,720 --> 00:16:21,320
Her hair.

247
00:16:21,400 --> 00:16:23,360
Oh, it's nice.

248
00:16:23,480 --> 00:16:26,360
Nice? Please, it's stunning.

249
00:16:27,120 --> 00:16:29,360
Wait till Jan sees it.
You're in for a busy night, my girl.

250
00:16:29,800 --> 00:16:32,440
I believe Mama Africa
paid us a visit today, James.

251
00:16:32,640 --> 00:16:34,440
You girls seem to know everything.

252
00:16:34,600 --> 00:16:37,440
Nothing happens on this island
without me finding out about it.

253
00:16:37,560 --> 00:16:39,440
Usually before it happens.

254
00:16:41,160 --> 00:16:42,080
So what's she like?

255
00:16:42,600 --> 00:16:43,760
She was only there five minutes.

256
00:16:43,840 --> 00:16:45,840
They started talking Xhosa
so I sent her packing.

257
00:16:45,960 --> 00:16:47,560
James speaks fluent Xhosa.

258
00:16:47,640 --> 00:16:50,520
- Really?
- He grew up with them on a farm.

259
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:53,280
He had a friend called...
What was his name?

260
00:16:53,680 --> 00:16:54,600
Man, who cares?

261
00:16:54,720 --> 00:16:57,360
- No, man, tell us.
- Please tell us, James.

262
00:16:57,440 --> 00:16:59,080
Bafana.

263
00:16:59,160 --> 00:17:01,080
James has got a photo of the two of them.
I'll get it.

264
00:17:01,200 --> 00:17:02,960
Gloria, no. Gloria!

265
00:17:03,040 --> 00:17:04,920
- No, I want to see it.
- Me, too.

266
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:07,280
Didn't know you were a farm boy, James.

267
00:17:07,360 --> 00:17:10,600
- I'm not a farm boy.
- Here it is. Look.

268
00:17:13,120 --> 00:17:15,520
Oh, cute. Look at the little Kaffir lover.

269
00:17:15,640 --> 00:17:16,960
I'm not a Kaffir lover!

270
00:17:18,840 --> 00:17:21,200
He's even got his arm
around the little nigger.

271
00:17:23,800 --> 00:17:26,480
That's it.
- Looks like a Kaffir-lover to me!

272
00:17:26,560 --> 00:17:28,640
I'm going fishing. Brent, get your rod!

273
00:17:29,760 --> 00:17:31,280
Look, Pa, a starfish.

274
00:17:32,480 --> 00:17:34,680
- That's nice, Natasha.
- Pa, I've got one.

275
00:17:34,800 --> 00:17:36,880
Hey, bring him through the rocks there.
Nice and slow, that's it.

276
00:17:38,160 --> 00:17:39,560
Hey, don't look at me, man.

277
00:17:39,680 --> 00:17:41,400
Don't look at me.
I'm not your bloody mother, man.

278
00:17:41,520 --> 00:17:43,320
- Give me that, Brent. Come here.
- Move it! Bastard!

279
00:17:43,440 --> 00:17:44,600
Natasha, come here, girl.

280
00:17:44,720 --> 00:17:46,440
Stay down. Stay there.

281
00:17:46,520 --> 00:17:48,120
- Pa, what about my fish?
- Never mind your fish.

282
00:17:48,240 --> 00:17:50,320
- Faster, faster, faster!
- Come, come, come!

283
00:17:50,440 --> 00:17:51,640
Are you trying to piss me off?

284
00:17:51,760 --> 00:17:53,200
- Get down, boy!
- But, Pa...

285
00:17:56,640 --> 00:17:59,000
Move it, you lazy bastards.

286
00:17:59,120 --> 00:18:03,440
All right then, we can go back now.
Come on. Okay?

287
00:18:06,280 --> 00:18:07,280
Move it!

288
00:18:09,560 --> 00:18:11,480
But what about my fish?

289
00:18:11,560 --> 00:18:14,360
I'm sorry, boy, but if those warders
had seen you, I'd be in big trouble.

290
00:18:14,480 --> 00:18:17,560
- Why?
- Prisoners aren't allowed to see children.

291
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:21,040
- Why not?
- Because they are here for punishment.

292
00:18:21,160 --> 00:18:22,160
Okay?

293
00:18:23,640 --> 00:18:24,880
Huh.

294
00:18:26,400 --> 00:18:28,080
This is from Motsadi's wife.

295
00:18:28,160 --> 00:18:34,120
"We have decided to boycott the bus service
as they have increased the fare by 80 cents."

296
00:18:35,520 --> 00:18:36,800
Cut it out.

297
00:19:09,080 --> 00:19:10,880
<i>The following,
please collect your letters.</i>

298
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:12,400
Sisulu.

299
00:19:14,760 --> 00:19:15,880
Mhlaba.

300
00:19:17,560 --> 00:19:21,520
Kathadra, hurry up.
Do you think I've got all day?

301
00:19:21,640 --> 00:19:25,440
Motsadi! Jonas Motsadi! Where's Motsadi?

302
00:19:31,320 --> 00:19:32,640
The rest of you are dismissed.

303
00:19:32,760 --> 00:19:36,880
Mr. Gregory, I found this in my cell.

304
00:19:38,040 --> 00:19:41,560
According to regulations,
no prisoner may be in possession

305
00:19:41,680 --> 00:19:44,720
of any newspaper or part thereof.

306
00:19:44,840 --> 00:19:49,800
Therefore, I am handing it over to you,
the proper authority.

307
00:19:56,280 --> 00:20:01,360
I am surprised that you did not look
at the article, Mr. Gregory.

308
00:20:17,160 --> 00:20:21,160
- Come on! Come on!
- That's it. Yes, go, Robben Island.

309
00:20:25,080 --> 00:20:26,040
Yes!

310
00:20:31,680 --> 00:20:33,680
Yes! Yes!

311
00:20:40,480 --> 00:20:41,480
Ah!

312
00:20:41,760 --> 00:20:43,920
- He's really got something, hey, darling?
- Very good.

313
00:20:44,040 --> 00:20:48,560
Gregory, for a postman,
you play a damn good game of rugby.

314
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:52,120
- Robben Island!
- Robben Island.

315
00:20:54,480 --> 00:20:57,240
I think it's time I had a word with Piet
about James.

316
00:20:57,360 --> 00:20:59,640
He's officer material,
there's no question about it.

317
00:20:59,760 --> 00:21:04,240
Oh, Joyce. I'll do your hair for free
for the rest of your life.

318
00:21:04,360 --> 00:21:07,280
Then I'm definitely going to talk with Piet.

319
00:21:08,320 --> 00:21:12,400
- Off to Cape Town for the weekend?
- Yeah, my mom's been dying to see the kids.

320
00:21:12,480 --> 00:21:13,880
It's been ages.

321
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:15,560
Then I'm going to give you
a little shopping list

322
00:21:15,640 --> 00:21:17,640
with a good mayonnaise at the top.

323
00:21:17,720 --> 00:21:19,640
I can't stand this prison issue stuff.

324
00:21:37,600 --> 00:21:38,920
- Granny!
- Granny!

325
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:41,040
Hello, my darlings!

326
00:21:41,920 --> 00:21:44,080
These are for you.
I found them on the beach.

327
00:21:44,200 --> 00:21:47,400
- Oh, they're beautiful.
- Hi, Mom.

328
00:21:47,480 --> 00:21:50,400
- How was the ferry?
- Fine. The sea was flat for a change.

329
00:21:50,520 --> 00:21:52,880
- Oh, good.
- I got you some fresh crayfish, Barbara.

330
00:21:53,320 --> 00:21:54,360
Oh!

331
00:21:55,040 --> 00:21:57,840
Never mind fresh, they're alive!

332
00:21:59,480 --> 00:22:03,000
Well, seeing as you didn't get seasick,
we can go shopping.

333
00:22:03,120 --> 00:22:06,880
- Nelson Mandela. That's awful.
- Yeah, it's a big responsibility.

334
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:09,200
James gets to check their mail
and monitors all their visits.

335
00:22:09,320 --> 00:22:11,120
That's restricted information, Gloria.

336
00:22:11,200 --> 00:22:14,160
Oh, for goodness sake,
Mom's not going to tell anyone.

337
00:22:14,240 --> 00:22:16,720
Gloria, come help me choose
some salad stuff quickly.

338
00:22:16,800 --> 00:22:19,560
I'll wait outside with the kids. Come here.

339
00:22:31,960 --> 00:22:33,400
The two of you, stand still.

340
00:22:33,520 --> 00:22:35,680
Passport. Where's your passport?
Let me see your passports.

341
00:22:35,800 --> 00:22:37,160
- Where's your passport?
- Your pass.

342
00:22:37,240 --> 00:22:39,160
You have no pass. Come, come, come.

343
00:22:39,480 --> 00:22:40,800
What's going on, Pa?

344
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:41,960
Passports. Where is your pass?

345
00:22:42,080 --> 00:22:43,160
They are checking for passes.

346
00:22:43,280 --> 00:22:45,840
- Come back here. Where's your pass?
- No! No!

347
00:22:47,880 --> 00:22:49,200
Come back, come back.

348
00:22:52,680 --> 00:22:54,520
Hey, freeze, Kaffir.

349
00:22:54,640 --> 00:22:56,640
I need some help over here.

350
00:22:59,800 --> 00:23:00,880
Get in the van!

351
00:23:06,360 --> 00:23:08,680
Where's your pass?
- I don't have it!

352
00:23:09,560 --> 00:23:10,960
You can't just leave the baby here!

353
00:23:11,040 --> 00:23:12,600
Hey, shut up!
It's none of your business.

354
00:23:12,720 --> 00:23:14,320
I'll take him. He's my daughter's child.

355
00:23:15,520 --> 00:23:19,320
It's all right. It's all right. It's all right.
It's okay.

356
00:23:22,040 --> 00:23:24,240
Maybe you should go talk to her.

357
00:23:26,640 --> 00:23:28,640
Another minute and these'll be done, okay?

358
00:23:44,880 --> 00:23:46,320
Feeling better?

359
00:23:49,680 --> 00:23:53,320
- Dinner's almost ready.
- Why didn't you stop that policeman?

360
00:23:53,400 --> 00:23:54,960
Because that's his job.

361
00:23:55,960 --> 00:23:58,640
To take the mommy away from the baby?

362
00:23:58,760 --> 00:24:03,400
No, but if the mommy doesn't have a pass,
then she's not allowed to be there.

363
00:24:03,480 --> 00:24:05,680
So they had to arrest her.

364
00:24:05,800 --> 00:24:07,400
Do we have a pass?

365
00:24:10,200 --> 00:24:12,120
- We don't need one.
- Why not?

366
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:14,120
Because we're white.

367
00:24:14,200 --> 00:24:17,640
- But is that fair, Pa?
- That's apartheid.

368
00:24:18,600 --> 00:24:21,480
It's the way we live, Natasha.
Whites on one side, blacks on the other.

369
00:24:22,080 --> 00:24:23,400
It's God's way, darling.

370
00:24:24,080 --> 00:24:26,200
Just like he doesn't
put a sparrow with a swallow.

371
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:29,480
Or a goose with a duck
or a cow with a buck.

372
00:24:29,560 --> 00:24:33,120
It's just not natural.
And we don't question God.

373
00:24:33,240 --> 00:24:34,280
Hmm?

374
00:24:58,280 --> 00:24:59,280
<i>Switchboard.</i>

375
00:24:59,400 --> 00:25:00,840
Pretoria 39001.

376
00:25:05,400 --> 00:25:06,360
Jordaan.

377
00:25:06,440 --> 00:25:09,280
<i>Gregory here.
A telegram just arrived for Mandela.</i>

378
00:25:10,480 --> 00:25:13,040
I know, the boy smashed head on
into a bridge.

379
00:25:14,120 --> 00:25:16,440
- Was it...
- What?

380
00:25:17,720 --> 00:25:19,640
You know. Is it an accident?

381
00:25:20,360 --> 00:25:22,680
<i>Of course.
You'll tell him personally, won't you?</i>

382
00:25:22,800 --> 00:25:23,840
Yeah.

383
00:25:23,960 --> 00:25:25,280
Let me know his reaction.

384
00:25:29,560 --> 00:25:30,800
What's up?

385
00:25:32,800 --> 00:25:35,000
Mandela's older son
was killed in a car crash.

386
00:25:36,920 --> 00:25:38,320
Good riddance.

387
00:25:40,600 --> 00:25:42,120
Do you have kids?

388
00:25:50,080 --> 00:25:52,280
Dig. Hey, work, you Kaffir!

389
00:26:00,440 --> 00:26:02,640
Who the fuck is Madiba?

390
00:26:02,720 --> 00:26:05,720
- Madiba is Mandela's clan name.
- Clan?

391
00:26:07,000 --> 00:26:08,320
Go tell him.

392
00:26:17,240 --> 00:26:20,920
Mandela, I'm sorry.

393
00:26:26,360 --> 00:26:29,320
Hey, what are you trying to do, man?
Get back to work.

394
00:26:29,400 --> 00:26:32,720
- Vann Niekerk, can I have a word?
- What?

395
00:26:32,840 --> 00:26:36,080
Regulation 16-A of the Prison Act states
that if a prisoner loses a family member

396
00:26:36,200 --> 00:26:39,000
they are entitled to two days off work
on compassionate grounds.

397
00:26:39,120 --> 00:26:42,520
- Compassionate grounds?
- Mandela's a lawyer.

398
00:26:42,640 --> 00:26:45,760
He knows these things. You don't want him
laying a charge against you, do you?

399
00:26:45,880 --> 00:26:48,160
I can escort him back to his cell, if you like.

400
00:27:35,320 --> 00:27:37,560
<i>Earlier today,
South African forces intercepted</i>

401
00:27:37,680 --> 00:27:41,480
<i>a large group of SWAPO insurgents
in South West Africa, killing 12...</i>

402
00:27:41,600 --> 00:27:43,640
- Would you like some more?
- Yes, please.

403
00:27:43,760 --> 00:27:44,680
<i>...and arresting five. There were no reports...</i>

404
00:27:44,800 --> 00:27:45,720
Thank you.

405
00:27:45,840 --> 00:27:47,880
<i>...of casualties on the South African side.</i>

406
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:48,920
<i>Dr. Christian...</i>

407
00:27:49,560 --> 00:27:51,480
Your food's getting cold.

408
00:27:53,880 --> 00:27:56,960
- What if it was murder?
- Not in front of the children.

409
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:02,000
James!

410
00:28:10,280 --> 00:28:11,480
They'd never do such a thing.

411
00:28:11,600 --> 00:28:15,640
I called the police in the Transkei.
I spoke to the duty officer.

412
00:28:15,760 --> 00:28:17,720
The more questions I asked,
the more he clammed up.

413
00:28:17,840 --> 00:28:20,080
Eventually he hung up on me.

414
00:28:20,160 --> 00:28:22,480
- That doesn't mean...
- Can I serve the jelly, Ma?

415
00:28:22,600 --> 00:28:24,120
Go ahead, darling.

416
00:28:27,440 --> 00:28:28,800
I was the one who told Jordaan

417
00:28:28,920 --> 00:28:30,760
that Thembi had a license, that he had a car.

418
00:28:30,840 --> 00:28:34,560
You're doing your job.
This country is at war, James.

419
00:28:35,800 --> 00:28:38,480
These people are savages.

420
00:28:39,360 --> 00:28:42,120
They don't want to share
this country with us. They hate us.

421
00:28:42,680 --> 00:28:46,600
If they had their way, they'd drive
every single white person into the sea.

422
00:28:47,280 --> 00:28:50,360
They'd leave us with nothing,
not even the clothes on our back.

423
00:28:52,160 --> 00:28:53,560
Yeah. I know.

424
00:28:56,200 --> 00:28:58,000
Come and have pudding.

425
00:30:08,480 --> 00:30:11,240
All right, you win this time.

426
00:30:14,840 --> 00:30:16,840
There won't be a next time.

427
00:30:16,920 --> 00:30:20,240
I'll come back and visit.
I promise I will, Bafana.

428
00:30:20,320 --> 00:30:23,280
My father says
you are going too far to ever return.

429
00:30:23,360 --> 00:30:24,760
I have to go.

430
00:30:24,840 --> 00:30:30,680
This tail will protect you
the rest of your days.

431
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:35,680
I will wear this forever.

432
00:31:31,840 --> 00:31:35,400
- I see you, Madiba.
- I see you, Mr. Gregory.

433
00:31:40,680 --> 00:31:43,920
I want you to know that I am very sorry
about the death of your son.

434
00:31:50,880 --> 00:31:56,800
Many times I tried to explain
to my son why I was always away from home,

435
00:31:57,520 --> 00:32:01,200
that I fight for a better world,
for my people and my family.

436
00:32:02,840 --> 00:32:04,840
I'm not sure he ever understood.

437
00:32:13,560 --> 00:32:16,760
Where did you learn to speak Xhosa,
Mr. Gregory?

438
00:32:17,400 --> 00:32:19,800
I grew up
near where you were born.

439
00:32:20,320 --> 00:32:23,920
Then you understand.
I need to bury my son.

440
00:32:24,960 --> 00:32:27,920
- You know they'll never allow it.
- I'm an honorable man.

441
00:32:28,040 --> 00:32:30,080
I give you my word I will not try to escape.

442
00:32:30,200 --> 00:32:31,520
It's not you.

443
00:32:32,880 --> 00:32:35,800
It's your communist friends,
what if they try to rescue you?

444
00:32:35,920 --> 00:32:38,360
What communist friends
are you referring to, Mr. Gregory?

445
00:32:38,480 --> 00:32:40,280
The whole of the bloody
African National Congress.

446
00:32:40,400 --> 00:32:43,000
Obviously, you have not read
the Freedom Charter.

447
00:32:43,120 --> 00:32:46,080
- I have.
- You have not. It is a banned document.

448
00:32:46,200 --> 00:32:47,600
Where would a sergeant
in the Prison Services

449
00:32:47,680 --> 00:32:49,480
get his hands on such a document?

450
00:32:49,560 --> 00:32:51,000
Well, I know about it.

451
00:32:51,080 --> 00:32:54,520
Then you would know
that all we want is equal rights for all,

452
00:32:54,640 --> 00:32:59,200
a world where people like you and I
can live peacefully side by side.

453
00:32:59,320 --> 00:33:01,320
That is what I wanted for my child.

454
00:33:02,920 --> 00:33:06,000
Surely, you want the same for your children.

455
00:33:10,920 --> 00:33:12,760
I wish to be alone now.

456
00:33:58,200 --> 00:34:03,160
- Motsadi, Mandela must eat.
- When our leader is ready to eat, he will eat.

457
00:34:08,200 --> 00:34:10,640
You tell him his son was buried yesterday,

458
00:34:10,760 --> 00:34:13,440
that the boy's mother was at the funeral.

459
00:34:27,560 --> 00:34:30,880
- Have you read the Freedom Charter?
- What?

460
00:34:31,840 --> 00:34:35,920
- The Freedom Charter, have you read it?
- No.

461
00:34:36,040 --> 00:34:38,400
Do you know what it's about?

462
00:34:38,520 --> 00:34:42,000
It's about the extermination of the whites.

463
00:34:43,960 --> 00:34:47,280
- Stuff like that, isn't it?
- How must I know?

464
00:34:49,080 --> 00:34:52,240
Pa, can we go watch Province
play against Natal on Saturday?

465
00:34:52,320 --> 00:34:54,000
- Maybe.
- Yes!

466
00:34:54,080 --> 00:34:56,280
I just need to quickly pop
into Roeland Street Prison.

467
00:34:56,400 --> 00:35:00,120
- But my mom's got lunch waiting for us.
- You go ahead. I'll be on the next train.

468
00:35:04,440 --> 00:35:06,480
But Roeland Street is not...

469
00:35:07,760 --> 00:35:09,320
Go, kids! Go.

470
00:35:27,280 --> 00:35:29,840
Excuse me, I understand there's
a section here containing banned literature.

471
00:35:29,920 --> 00:35:31,720
- Downstairs.
- Thank you.

472
00:35:48,280 --> 00:35:50,160
- Yes?
- I'm with the Prison Services.

473
00:35:50,280 --> 00:35:53,240
I'd like to take a look
at the Freedom Charter.

474
00:35:53,360 --> 00:35:54,640
Wait here.

475
00:36:03,160 --> 00:36:05,800
- You got authorization?
- What?

476
00:36:05,880 --> 00:36:10,040
This is a restricted area.
You need authorization to be here.

477
00:36:10,160 --> 00:36:13,760
Sergeant Gregory.
I'm a warder at Robben Island prison.

478
00:36:15,800 --> 00:36:18,880
So? You need authorization
from the security police

479
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:21,560
if you want to look at banned material.

480
00:36:24,800 --> 00:36:26,960
Listen here, Major Jordaan
